\begin_layout Title
Green and Ampt infiltration applied to the vadoze zone between rootzone and water table
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
T.N.Olstoorn
\end_layout

\begin_layout Date
July 2025,
 14
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Intro
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Unsaturated zone relations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are several analytic relations that described the moisture,
 hydraulic tension and unsaturated conductivity in the vadoze zone.
 Most famous are those by Brooks and Corey (1964) and Van Genughten (1980).
 These formulas are mere fittings of measured relations between these parameters.
 Those by Brooks and Corey (1964) (BC) are far simpler than the other ones and will be use here,
 also because the Van Genughten relations do not really fit the measurements better except for moisture tensions below the air-entry value.
 But that hardly matters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The reduced saturation 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta$
\end_inset

 is given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Theta=\frac{\theta-\theta_{r}}{n-\theta_{r}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the porosity,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 the absolute moisture content and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{r}$
\end_inset

 the residual moisture content,
 corresponding to the wilting point.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to BC we may approximate the reduced saturation by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Theta=\left(\frac{\Psi_{b}}{\Psi}\right)^{\lambda},\,\,\Psi>\Psi_{b}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

 is the capillary pressure head and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{b}$
\end_inset

 is the capillary pressure head at first satuarion or the air-entry pressure,
 i.e.
 the capillary pressure head that the top of the capillary fringe.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is called 
\begin_inset Quotes pld
\end_inset

pore-size distribution index
\begin_inset Quotes prd
\end_inset

.
 It must be dimensionless.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Inverting the expression leads to
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\Psi}{\Psi_{b}}=\Theta^{-1/\lambda},\,\,\Psi>\Psi_{b}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to Van Genughten (1980)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Theta=\left(\frac{1}{1+\left(\alpha\Psi\right)^{N}}\right)^{M}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Psi=\frac{\left(\Theta^{-1/M}-1\right)^{1/N}}{\alpha}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Hydraulic conductivity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The water relative conductivity 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{rw}$
\end_inset

 [-] and the relative air conductivity 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{ra}$
\end_inset

 according to BC is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
k_{rw} & =\Theta^{3+2/\lambda}=\Theta^{\epsilon}\\
k_{ra} & =\left(1-\Theta\right)^{2}\left(1-\Theta^{1+2/\lambda}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le k_{rw}\le1$
\end_inset

 while also 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le\Theta\le1$
\end_inset

.
 Hence if 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{rw}=0$
\end_inset

 then,
 obviously,
 also 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta=0$
\end_inset

.
 And if 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{rw}=1$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $3+2\lambda=0$
\end_inset

 which makes no sense.
 But for our needs 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{rw}=1$
\end_inset

 is the case for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta<1$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the Van Genughen expressions,
 these quantities are
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
k_{rw} & =\sqrt{\Theta}\left(1-\left(1-\Theta^{1/M}\right)^{M}\right)^{2}\\
k_{ra} & =\sqrt{1-\Theta}\left(1-\Theta^{1/M}\right)^{2M}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Green and Ampt (1911) infiltration Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the case that 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 is positive in downward direction.
 Noting that the capillary pressure 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi<0$
\end_inset

 in the unsaturated zone,
 applying Darcy's law yields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q=K\left(\Psi\right)\frac{dh}{dz}=K\left(\Psi\right)\left(\frac{d\left(\Psi+z\right)}{dz}\right)=K\left(\Psi\right)\left(\frac{d\Psi}{dz}+1\right)
\]

\end_inset

Where 
\begin_inset Formula $K=K\left(\theta\right)=K\left(\Psi\right)=K_{s}k_{rw}\left(\Psi\right).$
\end_inset

 Where 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{s}$
\end_inset

 is the saturated vertical hydraulic conductivity and 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{rw}$
\end_inset

 the relative hydraulic conductivity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\intop_{0}^{L}qdz & =\intop_{0}^{L}K\frac{d\Psi}{dz}dz+\intop_{0}^{L}Kdz\\
qL & =K_{0}\intop_{\Psi_{0^{-}}}^{\Psi_{z^{+}}}k_{rw}\left(\Psi\right)d\Psi+K_{0}L\\
qL & =K_{0}\intop_{\Psi_{0}}^{\Psi_{1}}k_{rw}\left(\Psi\right)d\Psi+K_{0}L
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K=K_{0}k_{rw}=K_{0}\Theta^{3+2/\lambda}=K_{0}\left\{ \left(\frac{\Psi_{b}}{\Psi}\right)^{\lambda}\right\} ^{3+2/\lambda}=K_{0}\left(\frac{\Psi_{b}}{\Psi}\right)^{2+3\lambda}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\intop_{\Psi_{0}}^{\Psi_{1}}k_{rw}d\Psi=\Psi_{b}\intop_{\Psi_{^{0}}/\Psi_{b}}^{\Psi_{1}/\Psi_{b}}\left(\frac{\Psi_{b}}{\Psi}\right)^{2+3\lambda}d\left(\frac{\Psi}{\Psi_{b}}\right)=\Psi_{b}\intop_{\Psi_{0}/\Psi_{b}}^{\Psi_{1}/\Psi_{b}}y^{-2-3\lambda}dy
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Psi_{b}\intop_{\Psi_{0}/\Psi_{b}}^{\Psi_{1}/\Psi_{b}}y^{-2-3\lambda}dy=-\frac{\Psi_{b}}{1+3\lambda}\left[y^{-1-3\lambda}\right]{}_{\Psi_{0}/\Psi_{b}}^{\Psi_{1}/\Psi_{b}}=\frac{\Psi_{b}}{1+3\lambda}\left[\left(\frac{\Psi_{b}}{\Psi_{0}}\right)^{1+3\lambda}-\left(\frac{\Psi_{b}}{\Psi_{1}}\right)^{1+3\lambda}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boxed{\intop_{\Psi_{0}}^{\Psi_{1}}k_{rw}d\Psi=\frac{\Psi_{b}}{1+3\lambda}\left[\left(\frac{\Psi_{b}}{\Psi_{0}}\right)^{1+3\lambda}-\left(\frac{\Psi_{b}}{\Psi_{1}}\right)^{1+3\lambda}\right]}
\]

\end_inset

As long as 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{1}$
\end_inset

 at the leading edge is greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{0}$
\end_inset

 at the trailing edge,
 the integral is positive,
 meaning accellerating the wetting front from relative to the tail.
 As an example,
 during infiltration 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{0}\le\Psi_{b}$
\end_inset

 while 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{1}\gg\Psi_{b}$
\end_inset

.
 In the fine-sand example cited by Charbeneau (2000),
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=3.7$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{b}=41$
\end_inset

 cm.
 And because 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{b}\le\Psi_{0}$
\end_inset

 we have for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{b}=\Psi_{0}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\intop_{\Psi_{0}}^{\Psi_{1}}k_{rw}d\Psi\approx\frac{\Psi_{b}}{1+3\lambda}[\approx1]\approx\frac{41}{1+3\times3.7}\approx3.4\,cm
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Increasing 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{1}$
\end_inset

 does not change anything.
 The only real increase of the integral can come from larger 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{b}$
\end_inset

 (thicker capillary fringe,
 i.e.
 more clayey) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{0}\le\Psi_{b}$
\end_inset

.
 For instance,
 in the case of ponding 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{0}$
\end_inset

would be negative.
 The problem is,
 that the BC-formula is not valid for negative 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Van Genughten-formule
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The same integration of 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{rw}d\Psi$
\end_inset

 when using Van Genughten's relation can only be executed numerically.
 The integral to be computed is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I=\intop_{\Psi_{0}}^{\Psi_{1}}k_{rw}d\Psi=\int_{\Psi_{0}}^{\Psi_{1}}\sqrt{1-\Theta}\left(1-\Theta^{1/M}\right)^{2M}\,d\Psi
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{1}$
\end_inset

 are the capillary pressures at the top and the bottom of the wetting column respectively and 
\begin_inset Formula $N=1/(1-M)$
\end_inset

,
 and,
 accoring to Van Genughten (1980)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Theta=\left(\frac{1}{1+\left(\alpha\Psi\right)^{N}}\right)^{M}
\]

\end_inset

We can just integrate numerically using 
\begin_inset Formula $scipy.integrate.quad(..)$
\end_inset

 and can compare the result with the analytic solution derived above for the much simpler Brooks and Corey relation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Van Genughten solution yields the same result ad the BC solution but it allows smaller values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 For the same values but 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{0}=0.001$
\end_inset

 the integral becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $41.5$
\end_inset

 cm and for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{0}=-40$
\end_inset

 cm it becoms 
\begin_inset Formula $79.6$
\end_inset

 cm.
 Anyway the capillary force across the column of infiltrated water is limited which is due to the low values of 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{rw}\left(\Psi\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is important to make sure the values used are in the range that keep the formulas are valid.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Green and Ampt (1911)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Green and Ampt (1911) developed a physically based approximation of the infiltration that has been widely used ever since.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Regard a vadoze zone of constant intial moisture 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

 pertaining to a reduced moisture 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 There is not water table with given head or 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

 at its top.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First assume that the infiltration rate 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 is given and is smaller than 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 Then,
 according to Darcy,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q=K\left(\frac{d\Psi}{dz}+1\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Integrate this from the top to the wetting front
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\intop_{0}^{L}qdz=\intop_{0}^{L}K\frac{d\Psi}{dz}dz+\intop_{0}^{L}Kdz
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
wL=K\intop_{\Psi_{0}}^{\Psi_{1}}k_{rw}\left(\Psi\right)d\Psi+Kk_{rw}\left(\Psi\right)L
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the column is saturated,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta=1$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{0}=n$
\end_inset

 we also have 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{rw}=1$
\end_inset

 so that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w=\frac{K_{0}}{L}\intop_{\Psi_{0}}^{\Psi_{1}}k_{rw}\left(\Psi\right)d\Psi+K_{0}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w=\frac{K_{0}}{L}\left\{ \intop_{\Psi_{0}}^{0}k_{rw}\left(\Psi\right)d\Psi+\intop_{0}^{\Psi_{1}}k_{rw}\left(\Psi\right)d\Psi\right\} +K_{0}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the case of ponding,
 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{rw}=1$
\end_inset

 so that with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{0}=-H_{w}$
\end_inset

 the ponding depth,
 first integral becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $+H_{w}$
\end_inset

 the ponding depth
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q=\frac{K_{0}}{L}\left\{ +H_{w}+\intop_{0}^{\Psi_{1}}k_{rw}\left(\Psi\right)d\Psi\right\} +K_{0}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second integral has the dimension of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

 and the outcome must be much smaller than 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{1}$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le k_{rw}\le1$
\end_inset

.
 It is set to to equal the effective capillary tension 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{z}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=L$
\end_inset

 .
 Therefore,
 we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q=\left(n-\theta_{0}\right)\frac{dz}{dt}=K_{0}\left\{ \frac{L+H_{w}+\Psi_{z}}{L_{t}}\right\} 
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The time to ponding follows from 
\begin_inset Formula $q=K_{0}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K_{0}=\left(n-\theta_{0}\right)\frac{dz}{dt}=K_{0}\left\{ \frac{L+H_{w}+\Psi_{z}}{L_{t}}\right\} 
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The UZF1 package
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The documentation is given in:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Niswonger RG,
 Prudic,
 DE,
 Regan RS (2006).
 The documentation of the Unsaturated-Zone Flow (UZF1) Package for Modeling Unsaturated Flow between the Land Surface and the Water Table with MODFLOW-2005.
 Chapter 19 of Section A:
 Ground Water,
 of Book 6,
 Modeling Techniques.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Richards equation with 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 positive in downward direction,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 moisture content,
 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 upward flux,
 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 evapo-transpiration rate and 
\begin_inset Formula $K\left(\theta\right)$
\end_inset

 vertical hydraulic conductivity follows from the principle of continuity combined with Darcy's law:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial\theta}{\partial t}=\frac{\partial q}{\partial z}-i
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\partial\theta}{\partial t} & =\frac{\partial}{\partial z}\left[K\left(\theta\right)\frac{\partial\psi}{\partial z}-K\left(\theta\right)\right]-i
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With 
\begin_inset Formula $K\left(\theta\right)\frac{\partial\psi}{\partial z}=K\left(\theta\right)\frac{\partial\psi}{\partial\theta}\frac{\partial\theta}{\partial z}=D\left(\theta\right)\frac{\partial\theta}{\partial z}$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $D\left(\theta\right)=K\left(\theta\right)\frac{\partial\psi}{\partial\theta}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial\theta}{\partial t}=\frac{\partial q}{\partial z}-i=\frac{\partial}{\partial z}\left[D\left(\theta\right)\frac{\partial\theta}{\partial z}-K\left(\theta\right)\right]-i
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ignoring capillary forces altogether,
 i.e.
 ignoring the diffusive term,
 the governing equation reduces to
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial\theta}{\partial t}+\frac{\partial K\left(\theta\right)}{\partial z}+i=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Method of characteristics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Writing the previous governing equation in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

,
 noting that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial K\left(\theta\right)}{\partial\theta}$
\end_inset

 is a soil property,
 we get
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial\theta}{\partial t}+\frac{\partial K\left(\theta\right)}{\partial\theta}\frac{\partial\theta}{\partial z}=-i
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Introducting the equation of variation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d\theta\left(t,z\right)=\frac{\partial\theta}{\partial t}dt+\frac{\partial\theta}{\partial z}dz
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
My approach to characteristics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the former two equations should be the same we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
dt & =1\\
dz & =\frac{\partial K\left(\theta\right)}{\partial\left(\theta\right)}=\frac{dK\left(\theta\right)}{d\theta}\\
d\theta & =-i
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And so,
 when following a characteristic,
 i.e.
 a line parallel to 
\begin_inset Formula $dz/dt=dK\left(\theta\right)/d\theta$
\end_inset

,
 we have the following characteristic relations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{dz}{dt} & =\frac{dK\left(\theta\right)}{d\theta}=v\left(\theta\right)\\
\frac{d\theta}{dt} & =-i\\
\frac{d\theta}{dz} & =\frac{-i}{\frac{dK\left(\theta\right)}{d\theta}}=\frac{-i}{v\left(\theta\right)}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These relations are the same as those in Niswonger et al.
 (2006) who uses a more formal or more abstract approach given next.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Anyway,
 when moving with the derived 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

-dependent velocity,
 and with 
\begin_inset Formula $i=0$
\end_inset

,
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 remains constant at along the characteristic,
 that is when moving with a speed 
\begin_inset Formula $dz/dt$
\end_inset

,
 which depends on 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
 This means that in a profile 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta-z$
\end_inset

,
 points with higher 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 with approach further down with lower 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 and finally overtake them,
 implying the formation of a sharp front of which the highest moisture content,
 the upstream side,
 is that of the highest moisture content of the overtaking wave.
 Where theta is increasing at upstream points,
 those points with become farther apart because of the velocity differences.
 Because of this mechanism,
 a drying front will immediately be stretched and become continuous.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I find it still difficult to grab the entirety of the process where the q(0,t) is varying randomly.
 It can be split in a number of waves each one day long with a constant 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 and let them evolve downward in time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a moisture profile 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\left(z,t=0\right)$
