\begin_layout Section
Representation of Wetting and Drying Fronts
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An increase in infiltration causes a wetting front to form;
 a decrease causes a drying front.
 Waves are used to represent both wetting and trailing fronts.
 Leading and trailing wave represent the two sides of a front.
 Attenuation of a lead wave occurs when a a trailing wave with a higher velocity overtakes the lead wave.
 This is of course a continuous process as long as the front does not overtake a leading front.
 When a trailing wave overtakes a lead wave,
 the water content of the lead wave becomes equal to that of the trailing wave.
 When the front overtakes a leading front,
 the same it true,
 while the velocity of the overtaking wave is now reduced to meet the lower 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{2}$
\end_inset

 it now faces,
 because 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1}-\theta_{2}$
\end_inset

 has now increased.
 A front that is overtaken is removed together with the now swallowed wave.
 The process of waves intersecting each other is termed a shock.
 At these instances,
 wave properties such as water content and flux become discontinuous at the instance a shock occurs (Abbott,
 1966).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A wetting front stays sharp,
 but a trailing wave elongates with time due to gravity.
 Trailing waves must,
